**To reproduce**
On a 1920 x 1080 monitor, create a graphics device in the game's constructor using

```
graphics = new GraphicsDeviceManager(this);
graphics.PreferredBackBufferWidth = 1280;
graphics.PreferredBackBufferHeight = 720;
graphics.IsFullScreen = true;
```

**What happens**
Getting the mouse position using `Mouse.GetState().X` shows that the mouse position is in screen coordinates, not client coordinates. That is, if the mouse cursor is all the way on the right-hand side of the screen, the x position is 1919.

**What I expected**
I expect the x position on the far right side to be 1279, not 1919, because in the game constructor the screen resolution was set to 1280 x 720 on full-screen. (This problem also applies to the y coordinate, of course.) This interferes, for example, with a simple UI library that uses the cursor position to determine whether the user is clicking on any elements; because then the clickable element really is somewhere else (and smaller) than it appears on the 1280 x 720 viewport that has been stretched to fit the screen as expected.

Platform is Windows 10 Home, x64, solution target is .NET 4.5, MG 3.5.
